    "abstract": "<jats:p>\n                  It is shown that estimates of the effective reproduction number\n                  <jats:italic>R</jats:italic>\n                  <jats:sub>\n                    <jats:italic>t</jats:italic>\n                  </jats:sub>\n                  for COVID-19 using standard packages such as E\n                  <jats:sc>pi</jats:sc>\n                  E\n                  <jats:sc>stim</jats:sc>\n                  can be reproduced very accurately using the expression\n                  <jats:italic>R</jats:italic>\n                  <jats:sub>\n                    <jats:italic>t</jats:italic>\n                  </jats:sub>\n                  =\n                  <jats:italic>c</jats:italic>\n                  (\n                  <jats:italic>t</jats:italic>\n                  )/\n                  <jats:italic>c</jats:italic>\n                  (\n                  <jats:italic>t</jats:italic>\n                  \u2212\n                  <jats:italic>\u03c4</jats:italic>\n                  ), where\n                  <jats:italic>c</jats:italic>\n                  (\n                  <jats:italic>t</jats:italic>\n                  ) is the incidence at time\n                  <jats:italic>t</jats:italic>\n                  and\n                  <jats:italic>\u03c4</jats:italic>\n                  the mean value of the series interval.\n                </jats:p>",
